{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a147ac3f-50f3-485e-b279-8a5739e4048c","content":"This repository doesn't contain specific documentation on this topic, but here's the general guidance for macOS NativeAOT crash dump recovery without `createdump`:\n\n### Steps to recover a crash dump on macOS (no `createdump`)\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — macOS disables them by default:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS places them in `/cores/`):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Check SIP** — System Integrity Protection can block core dumps for signed binaries. On dev machines you may need to disable it or use an unsigned build.\n\n4. **Use `lldb` to capture a dump post-mortem**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n\n5. **If no core file was written**, use `lldb` proactively:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./MyApp\n   (lldb) run\n   # after crash:\n   (lldb) process save-core crash.dmp\n   ```\n\n6. **macOS Crash Reports** — check `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` for `.ips` or `.crash` files generated automatically by ReportCrash.\n\n7. **Convert to a .NET-compatible dump** — if you need to analyze with `dotnet-dump`, note that NativeAOT dumps are best analyzed with `lldb` + the SOS plugin or the native debugger directly, since `createdump` metadata won't be present.\n\n**Key takeaway:** On macOS without `createdump`, rely on `lldb` (attach or post-mortem) and the OS-generated crash reports in DiagnosticReports.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d0b21005-5503-4427-8326-170f41e2e659","outputTokens":413},"id":"4f7ddf13-e805-4011-b84b-da406058bc6d","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:03:40.376Z","parentId":"86aa5443-7ec6-4994-aa6e-521d2f5dfb7c"}
